By participating in challenges you agree to the below rules. Please make sure you read them. If you break the rules, your entries will be removed and you might get banned from participating in future challenges.

* You are the owner of the uploaded photo and have the right to use it.
* There is a pet in the photo.
* In order to respect others’ efforts, photos which are not related to the challenge theme might be removed.
* The photo does not contain any violent, sexual, hatred promoting, insulting, or political messages. Moderators retain the right to remove any photos that break the rules.
* If the photo contains an animal that is clearly in distress, frightened, or uncomfortable, the photo will be removed.
* No “like4like” comments. If you spam other people, your account will be permanently blocked.
* Private contests are allowed as long as you don’t reward the winners with likes (hearts). 
* No insulting, abusive, or hate-related comments. If you use hate speech, your account will be permanently blocked.
* In order to vote, you have to log in. You can vote for more than one photo.
* You have the right to report inappropriate content by clicking on ‘’…‘’ in the bottom right corner so the moderators can react fast.
* You can post only one photo per day. Choose the best one! 
* Challenges will be active for one week.
* Your photo might be published on Dogo social media.

There is a built-in clicker in the Dogo app. The clicker is a sound signal to mark a behavior and precise moment for which the dog is rewarded. Science has proven that a praise or a treat has to be given within 0.8 seconds after correct behavior. If you choose not to use a clicker and instead use a food reward, you are unlikely to always deliver the treat in less than a second and the dog will refocus its attention on you and the treat, and not on the behavior it was performing. A clicker reduces training time by about 40%. You could instead use only a verbal command like, “Good,” “Yes,” but a clicker sound has an advantage that the sound it emits is specific and will be most likely heard only during training. It adds a dimension of clarity and precision to mark the moment the dog behaves as required.

Potty Training is one of the first challenges that dog parents face with their new furry family members. Every dog is different and the time to have your dog accident-free will vary greatly depending on the dog. Potty training is all about consistency and providing your dog with frequent access to appropriate elimination spots. This program will help you track your dog’s schedule to understand their biological clock and set reminders so you don’t skip those important potty breaks.
Set up a reminder to take your dog out\n\nA puppy of 2 months needs to potty every 2 hours, 3 months every 3 hours, etc. A dog should not wait for more than 6 hours.
